Template literals are string literals allowing embedded expressions and multi-line strings using backticks.

**Basic Template Literals**:
```javascript
const name = 'John';
const age = 30;

// String interpolation
const message = `Hello ${name}, you are ${age} years old!`;
console.log(message); // Hello John, you are 30 years old!

// Expressions in template literals
const result = `2 + 2 = ${2 + 2}`;
console.log(result); // 2 + 2 = 4

// Function calls in template literals
const greeting = (name) => `Hello, ${name.toUpperCase()}!`;
console.log(greeting('John')); // Hello, JOHN!
```

**Multi-line Strings**:
```javascript
// Multi-line without \n
const poem = `
Roses are red
Violets are blue
JavaScript is awesome
And so are you!
`;

console.log(poem);
```

**Tagged Template Literals**:
```javascript
// Custom template processing
function highlight(strings, ...values) {
  return strings.reduce((result, string, i) => {
    const value = values[i] ? `<strong>${values[i]}</strong>` : '';
    return result + string + value;
  }, '');
}

const name = 'John';
const age = 30;
const highlighted = highlight`Name: ${name}, Age: ${age}`;
console.log(highlighted); // Name: <strong>John</strong>, Age: <strong>30</strong>
```

**Advanced Template Literal Features**:
```javascript
// HTML templates
const user = { name: 'John', age: 30 };
const html = `
  <div class="user">
    <h2>${user.name}</h2>
    <p>Age: ${user.age}</p>
  </div>
`;

// Conditional rendering
const isLoggedIn = true;
const nav = `
  <nav>
    ${isLoggedIn ? '<a href="/profile">Profile</a>' : '<a href="/login">Login</a>'}
  </nav>
`;

// Loops in templates
const items = ['Apple', 'Banana', 'Orange'];
const list = `
  <ul>
    ${items.map(item => `<li>${item}</li>`).join('')}
  </ul>
`;
```

**Use Cases**:
- String interpolation
- HTML templates
- SQL queries
- Configuration files
- Error messages
- Dynamic content generation

Template literals make string manipulation much more powerful and readable!
